{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_tango_ver02/data/sn84026749/100492556/1908030901/0456.xml":{"full_text":"ANNA GOULD\nWILL RETURN\nT0 DWH LANE\nHas Sailed or Is at\nFrench Country Estate\nPreparing for Voyage\nAcross Atlaniic.\nHurried Departure Gives\nColor to Story of Her\nMarriage to de\nSagan.\nLL ARID, MMAailLL JAR iINC. UWL IF VR\nlieved to be either on her way to the\nUnited States or to be at the Chateau\nMarais preparing to sail Wednesday.\nThough Mme. Gould announced last\nweek that she contemplated a visit to\nher native land this spring, the news\nof the completion of her plans for de\nparture fell like a thunderbolt. What\namounts a!most to a flight from France\ninelines her fri\u00e9nds to accept as true\nthe story in the Cri de Paris that she\nand Prince Helle de Sagan were mar\nried recently in Germany,\n\n\n1\nMme. Gould herself explicitly and ab\nsolutely denied the Cri's assertions, but\nthoss best acquainted with her affairs\nand those of the prince take it that\nshe prefers to be herself the first to ac\nquaint members of her family with and\n{0 secure their approval to an already\ni\n\naccomplished fact.\nDischarges Her Servants,\nThe Gould household was informed of\nMme. Gould's plans Saturday, but her\nannouncement did not reach the public\nuntil today. Then it came from the\nservants, Their story is that Mme.\nGould called them together at her Paris\nhome Saturday afternoon, teld them\nshe was compelled to leave suddenly\nfor America, where she would remain\nthree months, and discharged them all\non the spot.\nThe servants replied by an angry\ndemand for three weeks\u2019 notice or their\nwages for that length of time, as ac\ncording them under the French law,\nbut say they met with a point blank\nrefusal.\nOne version is that she even asked\nthem to wait three months for the\nwages already due, and that the same\nrequest was made of the tradesmen\nthe household has patronized. Then\nshe left the house with her three chil\ndren, and the janitors assert, thal\nshe started at once for New York.\nOther reliable information is, however,\nthat she has gone or to the Chateau\nMarais to make her final preparations,\nand has booked passage for Wednes\nday.\nMay Lese Half of Fortune.\nIf it is true that de Sagan and Count\nBoni de Castellane\u2019s former wife are\nactu wedded there is every reason\nfor diplomatic manageinent, inasmuch\ngs half of the bride's fortune would\npass, under the terms of her father's\nwill, out of her possession in the event\nof a marriage unapproved by a family\ncouncil.\nThere have been repeated rumors,\nfrom the time the de Castellane divores\nsuit was begun, that Mme, Gould was\nto wed the Prince de Sagan as soon\nas she was legally able to do so. These\nreports were denied from time to time,\nbut invariably sprang again to life.\nBoni Fought Cousin.\nCount Boni de Castellane evidently ac\ncopted them as true, for he explained\nhis recent attack on the prince, when\nbrought to trial for assault, on the\nground that he considered the prince\nan improper person to be siep-father to\nhis children.\nThe prince and Count Bonl are cous\nins. They clashed twice in public\u2014oncs\nabout a year ago and again only a few\nweeks ago, when Boni followed a meet.\ning in church by spitting in his cousin's\ntace and abusing him in every term in\nthe Gallic vocabulary.\n\nThe prince fell, or wag knocked, dowr\nduring the encounter, and asserted thal\nBoni's brother Jean helped the forme:\nto beat him. Maintaining that in out.\nnumbering him the Castellanes had put\nthemselves outside the rules of the code\nof honor, he did not challenge them, but\nsued Boni for one franc damages. Jie\nwon his case, and Boni was also fined\n2 frencs, or about $4. Boni contended\nthat Sagan failed to send a challenge\nbecause it was impossible for him tc\n8nd ecceptable seconds.\nWedded in Germany.\nThe Cri de Paris\u2019 story was that Di\nand Mme, Gould were wedded fir\noe of the smaller German towns; thal\nthe prince contemplated naturalizatior\nin Germany, where he has titles more\nimposing than those he bears in France\nthat the Kaiser encouraged the mar\nriage, and that Sagan had assurance:\ntrom the monarch of honors at court\nand perhaps a German principality. Hz:\n2 to be as extravagant as Coun\nni.\nSagan\n\nMme. Gould was not perpuitied, unde\nher divorce decree, to take her childre:\nout of France without her former hus\nband's consent, but it was underetoo\nseveral days ago that this had alread)\nbeen secured.\na\nTO YOURSELF keep vour teeth in\nproper egondition. Save pain and ex\npense by having them attended to at\nonce. Our prices are reasonable.\nAll Work\n(ITY 1) Guaranteed\nam\n$5.00 Set of Teeth.... $3.50\n$7.50 Set of Teeth.... $5.00\n$10.00 Set of Teeth.... $7.50\n$15.00 Set of Teeth... .$10.00\n22-kt. Gold Crowns, $3 and $5\nBRIDGEWORK, $3 and $5\nFillings, 50c up.\nPainless Extracting, 50c.\nRoyal Dentists, 707 G St. NW.\nNear Cor. 7th, 8acond Floor Front.\nHours\u2014Dally, 0 Sunday, i0-te L\nTOYA DENTIST\nWill Force Venezuela\nTo Yield to Our Terms\nIs Ultimatum Expected\n\nDrastic Action Looked for in Congress This\nWeek on Reading of Letters Relative to\nSeizing of Americans\u2019 Property.\n\nStrained relations with Venezuela,\nwhich may result in the rupture of\ndiplomatic Iutercourse between this\ncountry and President Castro's gov\nernment, are expected to follow the\nearly publication of the correspondence\nregarding the trea nt of American in\nvestors in Venezuela, and the subse\nquent action of Congress thereon.\nCalled for by a resolution introduced\nby Senator Lodge, at the direct re\nguest of the President, these documents\nwiil be sent to the Senate this week.\nIt is believed by some members of the\nForeign Relations Committee, who have\nbeen made acquainted with the situa\ntion, that the more recent letters which\nheve passed between. the American\nState Departmeht and the Venezuelan\nforeign office, have been of a character\nsuch as to create a barrier in the ne\ngotiations, and to render continuation\nof the present situation impossible.\n\n\n\ni\n\nThere still 18 a quesfion as to what\nCongress may do under the circum\nstances, but the general impression\namong Senators, is that a r\u00e9solution\nwill be adopted giving the President\nfull power to take such action as he\nmay see fit to secure justice for the\nAmerican complainants.\n\n\n1\n\u201cCongress,\u201d sald a leading member\nof the Foreign Relations Committee (O\nday, \u201cmight, of course, gc as far as to\ndeciare war, but IT do not believe the\nmatter is of such importance as 10\nrLICKINGER HELD;\n$2,000 BAIL FIXED\n\nWitnesses Relate Story of\nAlleged Attack on\nFrenchman,\nCharged with having assaulted Rene\nde Serviere with intent to kill, Otto\nFlickinger, erstwhile teacher of Ger\nnian in the Berlitz School of Languages,\nwas held by Judge Kinball in the Po\nlice Court this morning. His ball was\nfixed at $2000. Effort is being made to\n\u00a2btain the sum.\n\n\n\nAside from a slight bruise above the\nleft eye, da Seviere shows no. evidences\nof the alleged at: He testified that\nwhile going to hi: rooms at 715 Four\nteenth street, he was assaulted by\nFlickinger, who was hiding behind a\ndoor with a large dirk fm his hand.\n\ngood\nPoliceman Cramer went on the stand\nand stated that his attention had been\nattracted by cries of murder, and that\nhe had broken the door at thie Berlitz\nSchool! and founa Flickinger and de\nServicre clinched on the first landing.\nThe latter was striving desperately to\nbeat off Flickinger with his fists, and\ni\n\nFlickinger was lunging his knife time\nafter time iniv his opponent's bedy, he\n\nsaid.\nThroughout the trial Flickinger sat\nwith arms folded, apparently manifest.\ning little interest in evidence against\nhim. The case will be heard before the\ngrand jury within the next few weeks.\n\n\u2018m0 ATTEND AERO BANQUET.\nMany Washington balloon enthusiasts\nwiil go to New York next Saturday\nevening to attend the Aero Club ban\nquet. Prof. Willis L. Moore, chief of\nthe Weather Bureau, and Lieutenant\nLehm, U. B. A, now conducting aero\nnautic experiments at Fort Myer, Va,\nwill be among the principal speakers.\n\nThe Business Outlook\nis better than we think.\nMr. Frank A. Munsey has been writing a series of\narticles for his magazine which are full of good cheer.\nThe third article in the series is in the March num\nber of Munsey's Magazine. It shows pretty clearly\nthat the country isn\u2019t going io the dogs and #sserts that\nconditions are steadily and surely improving\u2014improving\nin a healthy normal way.\nWhy Not Get Over the Blues?\nIf you are blue why not let a little sunlight into your\nsoul and be happy: ow is the time to get your work\nin if you want to make money and if you want to get on\nthe sunny slope of the mountain.\nMr. Munsey\u2019s articles will help you to do this.\nThey are full of sound commonsense, and are doing a\nworld of good in reestablishing confidence and giving\nan uplift to, courage. Get the February Munsey if you\ncan and read the article in that issue. Be sure to get\nthe March number anyway. It is still on sale. If your\ndealer has sold his supply he can get you a copy. In\nfact, he can get you the Febroaty number.\nOn all News-stands. 10 Cents.\nThe Frank A. Munsey Company, New York\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES, MONDAY, MARCH 9, 1908.\n\nwarrant that, and I belleve Castro\nrealizes this.\n\u201cThe United States has indorsed the\nprincipal that nations ought not to re\nsort to gunboats to collect debis. We\nonce scolded Germany and England for\ndoing that with Venezuela, and we can\nnot very well go ahead and do the\nsame thing ourselves.\n\u201cSome Senators, however, are of the\nopinion that in this instance it ls not\na mere question of the collection of\ndebts. There has been actual confisca\ntion of property belonging to American\ncitizens by President Castro, and the\nsequestration of the proceeds of that\nproperty for his own use and benefit. I\nam not prepared to say whether the\nDrago doctrine would eovey this phase\nof the case or not. But my own opinion\nis that we ought to punch Castro's\nhead, figuratively, speaking, for his im\npudence.\u201d\u2019\nThe last sentence of this interview Is\nindicative at once of the tgne of the\nreplies which have been received from\nVenezuela to the representations of the\nUnited Stgtes, and of the resentment\ncaused th\u00a5rebv in the mind of this one\nSenator. Ii is Xnown, moreover, that\nhe also voiced 1\u201ce views of members of\nthe Administratigpg and of other Sena\ntors in using this> expression.\n\nAnother Senator, also a member of\nthe Foreign Relations Committee, to\nday gave it as his opinion that if Cen\ngresa places the matter in the hands\nof the President to settle, as he expected\nwould be the case, he would push diplo\nmatic representations to the last limit,\nand, this falling, would send an ult.\nmatuvm to Presiderdt Castro, and be pre\npared to back It up.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nRECEPTION FOR HEXAMER\nGERMAN SOCIETIES PLAN\nTre. C. J. Hexamer, of Philadelphia,\nf:=ident of the National GermanAmer\nfray Alliance, will be the guest of honor\nat :n elaborate reception und banquet\nto be given by the United German So\ncleties of this city March i8. In addi\ntion to the society membership others\nof German or German-American extrac\ntion will participat2, the affair promis\ning to be one of ths largest held by the\nUnited Societies.\nsisi\n\n\n\ni\n\nA program, consisting of ~ongs and\nepeeches, is being prepared. Represen\ntatives Richard Bartholdt, A. J. Barch\nfeld, W. A. Rodenberg, Julius Kahn,\nand others of national promirne. nea have\n\u2018been asked to address the meeting, The\nUnited rs will be presert and ren\nder several! chorus numbers.\nThe National German-American Al\nliance has a membership of over 2,000,060,\nTHOMAS AUTO RAGER\nUNDER NEW DRIVER\nCHEYENNE, Wyo, March 9.Mon\ntague Roberts, who has driven the\nAmerican car, leader \u2018n the New York\nto Paris autemoblle race, from New\nYork to Cheyenne, relinquished his post\nyesterday when this city was reached.\nE. Linn Matthewson will take the car\nto Ogden. The car arrived here at 1:50\no'clock p. m.\n\n\nThe automobile was met east of\nCheyepne by a procession af Cheyenne\nDenver automobilists, and was\net on reaching this city by a large\nrowd, with cheers, ringing of bells\naud blowing of factory whistles.\nNeb., March \u00a7.\u2014Repairs to\nthe Italian car in the New York to\nParis auto race have not yet heen com\npleted, and it will not start till, tomor\nrew morning.\nA dispaten from Rochelle, Ill, says\nthe German car and the French car,\nNo. 2, have stopped there for today.\nPRESIENTS NIEGE\nBREAKS ENGAGEMENT\nMiss Corinne Douglas Rob\ninson Not to Wed\nDr. Draper.\nNEW YORK, March 9.-It is an\nnounced on the best authority that the\nengagement which existed between\nMiss Corinne Douglas Robinson and Dr.\nGeorge H. Drape: has been broken by\nmutual consent. Except to relatives\naud a few of their most intimate\nfriends this anncuncement will cause\nno small amount of surprise, as it was\nunderstood they would be married in\nthe easly part of June.\n\nMiss Robinson is the only laughter of\nMr. and Mrs. Douglas Robinson and a\nniece cf President Roosevelt. Her \u00e9fi\ngagement to Dr. Draper was premature~\nly announced about a year ago, when\nshe was in Rome with her parents. Mr.\nand Mrs. Robinson had intended to\nmake the formal ennouncement on thelr\nreturn to New York in June, bul the\nengagament was taken up by other per\nsons. After a prompt dental on this\nside of the ocean it was finally acknowl\nedged by Mr. and Mrs. Robinson in\n\"Rome.\nDr. Draper is a son of the late Dr.\n\u2018William H. Draper and a grandson of\nthe late Charles A, Dans. He was\ngraduated froin Harvard in 158 and\nafterward attended the medical school\nthers. Fer nearly two years he has\nbeen an interne in the Presbyterian\nHospital, where he now is.\nThe reason for the bre\u00e9akh:g of the\nengagement is said to have Leen a very\nscusible one; that each of the voung\npersons, while having the highest re.\ngard for the other, found they were\nnot suited to each other, and therefore\ncaine to what they considered the best\nconclusion\noth Miss Robinson and Dr. Draper\nare great favorites and were much In\nevidence socially during the winter,\nhaving been included at the leading\nfashionable events of the season.\nPARDON OF STOESSEL\nEXPECTED FROM GZAR\nST. PETERSEURG, March \u00a7.\u2014The\nCzar has commuted the sentence of\ndeath imposed against General Stoessel\nfor surrendering Port Arthur te ten\nvears\u2019 imprisonment in a fortress, and\nit is expected a full pard n will shortly\nfollow.\nThe impression is that Nicholas would\nhave set the Port Arthur defender free\nat once but for the opposition of his\nwar office, which hated Stoessel for his\nstrictures concerning the unprepared\nness of the fortress at the outnreak of\nthe war with Japan.\nThe military court which tried the\ndecided that he yielded to Gen\neral Nogi before his resources had been\ncompletely exhausted. The Japanese\nthemselves expressed much sympathy\nfor the man who held out so long\nagainst them, and declared he did every\nthing passible.\nStocssel has never enjoyed health\nsince the hardst ips of the siege.\nHOLD FUNERAL TODAY\nFOR PAUL P. LYNCH\nThe funeral of Paul P. Lynch, the\nyoung Census Office clerk, who died\nshortly after being taken to the\nEmergency Hospital Friday afterroon,\nwas held this morning from the chapel\nof Sardo Co.'s undertaking es\ntablishment, 8 H street northeast, at\n8:30 o'clock. The body was taken to\nSt. Patrick's Church, where mass was\nsaid. Interment was in Arlington.\nMr. Lynch, who lived at New\nJe avenue northwest, was seized\nwith a fainting spell at Ninth and B\nstreets northwest, Friday afte: noon, bul\nrefused at first to go to the hospital\nHe was later taken there in a trol\nwagon, dying shoteiy afterw; AR\nexamination showed him to_be suffer\ning with Bright's disease.\nBUSINESS BOOMING\nFINANCIERS HAPPY\nResumption of Work in\nWest Told in Wiresto\nWall Street.\nfee dfmofodel\nNEW YORK, March 9 Wall Street\nwas today highly elated over dispatches\nindicating a remagkable resumption. of\nbusiness in the West. The Jones\nLaughlin Steel Company, of Pittsburg,\nhas ordered resumption of work on its\nnew $15,000,000 steel plant at Aliguippa,\nand the machinery builders who had the\ncontracts ror the great heavy machines\nhave heen ordered to continue their\nwork with all speed.\nofferte!\n\n\nThe Westinghouse Eiectric and Manu\nfacturing Company has ordered tne\nworking force increased 25 per cents\nStructural steel mills have booked orders\nfor 50,000 tons of steel since February 1,\nand the rail mills have booked orders in\nIa. save time for 150,000 tons of steeg\nr\n\neatne\nRUMOR\non wr en\npra)\nTOR JR JR, JP J JN, J,\nRA\" Ae\nCoal mines which have been idle since\n\u2018Noven per have been reopened, and are\nworkin g full forces. Lake navigating\nhas xen ordered to begin March 15,\ninstead of April 1, as usual\n\nAdvices from Omaha say that entire\nconfidence has been restored in that\ngection of the West, and that one big\ncontract just let is for car repairing\nshops to cover 300 acres, and for 500 cot.\ntages for the workmen,\n.__ 8\nwlerted wwe\nLa a}\nuilding permits in that section show\na handsome increase over a similar pe\nriod last year, and everything indicates\nrenewed commercial activity on a\nETeater scale.\nden ostosfe sd\n(a)\nTurn Your Face\ninto Dollars\ntod\ntouted\nATA\nLW)\nMany a Man Has Failed Because His\nFeee Was a Pieture of Calamity.\neri wieviele]\nIt takes sunshine to produce a rose,\na perfect rose. And so man, to be suc\ncessful, must have sunshine inside. The\nlife which has it not, which hac no\nhealth and no happiness, is sour\u2019 surly,\n5\no\n\n4\nnant\nistic, and a failure, 